In this week's issue, TIME's Belinda Luscombe looks at the wave of alimony reform sweeping across the U.S. and the women driving the change: the first and second wives who think it's time for the old rules to go.

(read a preview here: http://ti.me/18YAJut)

Today, at 12:30 PM [ET], Luscombe will be taking over our Facebook page to discuss divorce's changing future. There are multiple factors in question, as she writes: Should men still have to pay alimony when women can now make (almost) as much as men? And if we abolish alimony, how do older women without job skills get by?

What do you think? Leave your questions and thoughts in the comments below.

"There is nothing wrong with you. You're amazing. I love you. When I look at you I see a complex human being with awesome potential but some others will look at you and see a thug. Even if their only evidence is your skin. Their racism relates to larger anxieties and problems in America that you didn't create. When someone is racist toward you—either because they've profiled you or spat some slur or whatever—they are saying they have a problem. They are not speaking about you. They're speaking about themselves and their deficiencies."

- Toure to young black boys after the shooting of Travyon Martin in this week's print issue, on newsstands Friday.

Many black families have been forced into uncomfortable conversations since the Feb. 26 killing of 17-year-old Trayvon Martin. Blood memories of strange fruit have been stirred.

status_message:
At Easter 1966, millions of Americans picked up what would become one of the most notable magazine covers in the history of the genre: TIME's stark question asking "Is God Dead?" In retrospect, the cover—and the much-less-remembered actual piece that ran with it—represented a mainstreaming of the spirit of dissent and debate that characterized the era. The cover was back in the news last week with word that the main theologian profiled in the piece, William Hamilton, had died. Hamilton was 87; at the time of the 1966 article, he was a professor at Colgate Rochester Divinity School.

Interested? Don't miss Jon Meacham's fascinating column on TIME.com looking back at Hamilton's story and one of the most controversial covers in TIME's history: http://ti.me/xpmomh

link_name: Top 10 Best-Selling TIME Issues

status_message:
On the morning of Sept. 11, 2001, TIME's Nancy Gibbs got a phone call from our then-managing editor Jim Kelly. Gibbs was at home in Westchester, NY, away from the chaos filling Manhattan where the TIME offices are located. "He said, 'I wanted to know if you're game to write.' And I said, 'Of course. Which story do you want me to do? And he said, 'Well, I only want one story.'" 

Gibbs spent the next 36 hours writing the the cover story for TIME's special report on the events of 9/11, receiving nearly 1200 e-mails from the entire staff of TIME who hit the streets of New York to report for her. Here, you can watch her tell the story of how it all came together.
link_name: Behind the Scenes: TIME's Original 9/11 Cover Story

status_message:
It took one researcher four days to sift through an archive of more than 5,000 photo negatives to find this photo of Bill Clinton with Monica Lewinsky at a Democratic fund raiser in October 1996. 

Photographer Dirck Halstead credited his practice of preserving photos for the cover image, which TIME sat on for five months before using it to accompany the right story.

Read the cover story: http://ti.me/Hdc6sn

status_message: D.A. Pennebaker's documentary on Bob Dylan's 1965 tour of the United Kingdom "Don't Look Back" is released. TIME reporter Horace Judson's interview with Dylan is featured in a scene that shows Dylan heckling Judson and TIME. "The poor souls, they were sent out to interview him and they didn't know much about him," Pennebacker told TIME in 2007. "He turned it into a circus. He was enjoying himself. But I never felt that he was being particularly mean in those interviews."
link_name: Bob Dylan - Interview With Time Magazine 1965

status_message: Singer-songwriter Bob Dylan is first covered by TIME as a young artist trying to make a name for himself on the New York folk scene. "The tradition of Broonzy and Guthrie is being carried on by a large number of disciples, most notably a promising young hobo named Bob Dylan. He is 21 and comes from Duluth. He dresses in sheepskin and a black corduroy Huck Finn cap, which covers only a small part of his long, tumbling hair. He makes visits to Woody Guthrie's hospital bed, and he delivers his songs in a studied nasal that has just the right clothespin-on-the-nose honesty to appeal to those who most deeply care. His most celebrated song is Talkin' New York – about his first visit to the city, during the cold winter of 1961, when he discovered "Green Witch Village."
link_name: Folk Singing: Sibyl with Guitar
